# Gemini developer Search Engine Marketing (SEM) overview

## Developer marketing objectives

1. Drive reach and awareness for ‘Build with Gemini’
2. Drive Gemini trial through AI Studio
3. Onboard and engage developers to Google AI Studio (showing a clear path to Vertex AI)

## Effective SEM best practices

- Headlines have a 30 character limit, Descriptions have a 90 character limit
- You can have up to 15 headlines and 4 descriptions per ad, with a campaign limit of 3 responsive search ads
- Headlines should include at least a few variations that contain your brand name and a few variations that include a call to action
- Calls to action should reflect intended user outcomes like clicking "Get API Key" buttons on site for example
- Likewise, Descriptions should include both a call to action, your brand name and details about value propositions, how your product is solving pain points, or how our product is differentiating itself from competitors
- Ads should align with the landing page copy as much as possible, this will improve ad rank and delivery, in this case please reference: https://ai.google.dev
- Ads should also include references to target keywords that trigger our ad delivery. Here is a list of keywords that are currently live.
- Never use the word "free" in the headlines or descriptions. Avoid mentions of "free trials" or "trying it for free", or variation on that theme.

## Target audience

- Developers in the explore and learn mindset:

  - "I like to stay ahead of developer news and I’m curious about Google’s AI tools"
  - "I’m in my first steps of my AI development journey"
  - "I’ve heard about this new model, Gemini, from Google..."

- Developers already using competitor model solutions (ex. OpenAI API, Microsoft Copilot)
- Developers who are looking for models for specific use cases

  - "Search embeddings" or "RAG"/"retrieval augmented generation" or "text generation models"

- Practitioners leveraging coding assistants and AI-enabled tools to accelerate workflows, some integrating AI via APIs
- Product and strategy owners assessing the value of AI in their business, and leveraging genAI to enhance productivity and creativity

## We want developers to

- Think: "Google is a leader in the AI game. Gemini looks exciting. I want to try it."
- Feel: "Excited that I will be able to build with Google's most advanced model."
- Do: Visit AI Studio, get an API key, and prompt Gemini Pro.

## Ad copy test dimensions

- Product focused
  - Awareness/education of product ("do I know what this product is and what is does?")
  - Value of product
  - Consideration of product ("is this product one I would use?")
  - Intent to use ("this is a product I see myself using")
- Ad focused:
  - This ad is helpful/engaging
  - This ad builds trust in the brand
- Search strategy:
  - Help developers navigate multiple generative AI offerings from Google.
  - Target upper funnel keywords that indicate a user is curious about AI and app development (ex: "generative AI," "artificial intelligence," and "uses of AI") as well as branded terms like "Gemini AI model" and drive to the "Build with Gemini" landing page where they can learn more.

### Review of Set 1

Critique: Headlines and descriptions are a bit too general, We have a few headlines that refer to "Build", but it seems we have more headlines that are just about "unlocking AI" or general brand callouts. I also only see 1 description that actively mentions "development" and a few others that call out "apps"
Instead: It would be great to get more variation on Developer focused messaging, especially around different day to day tasks that Gemini can help with

Critique: I don't see any CTA (call to action) call outs in the headlines (i.e "Get Started" or "Get the API Key Today")
Instead: it would be great for headlines to segment out chunks of headlines by type. We usually have 3 types of headlines we use: Brand name, Value Prop/Feature, Call to Action. This may help generate more results-driven headlines.

Critique: "Unlock", "Empower" and "Discover" -type language is not really present on the Gemini site. While we like the tone and impact of "Unlock", this misalignment can result in unwanted Consumer clicks, or ad ranking declines due to Google not finding similar language in our site content
Instead: If we can incorporate more action-based terms from the site, I think we'll speak more effectively to our target audiences. I see terms on-site like "Integrate", "Build", "Versatility", "Experience" as some potential swaps here

## Review of set 2

Critique: This ad copy set is much more effective at action-based callouts in the headline, but I would flag a small concern over little variation between headlines to align with the 3 headline types flagged in set 1.
Instead: use a simplistic headline with just our Brand, or "Build with Gemini".

Critique: question headlines are interesting, but this may be flagged as an "Editorial" violation.
Instead: Do not use questions in headlines

Critique: Descriptions appear to have 2 spaces after a period, not sure if this is intentional, but this adds to our character limit.
Instead: use one space after a period.

## Landing page content

ai.google.dev is inclusive of both product offerings:

1. "fast and free" Google AI Studio, as well as
2. contextual enterprise on-ramps to Vertex AI on Google Cloud, which developers can use if they are ready to scale their applications.

## Success metrics

Primary: Conversion rate / Cost per conversion (CPA)
Current: conversion defined as click on the "get API key" button on ai.google.dev
Future: tie conversions to usage on AI Studio (unable to track now due to missing cookie bar)
Secondary: click thru rate
